I created a TaskType that collects test by parsing the Machine Specifications results files, since there is no built-in parser and it does not follow the xUnit conventions.  I have confirmed my code correctly places test results in the proper buckets.  But Bamboo is reporting the collected tests incorrectly.

{code}
builder.addFailedTestResults(failedResults);
builder.addSkippedTestResults(ignoredResults);
builder.addSuccessfulTestResults(successfulResults);
{code}

I've attached the output file that was parse to show I have 8 total tests.  1 of which has failed and 1 of which is ignored.

So this screen gets it partially right.

!screenshot-4.png!

But these are wrong 

!screenshot-1.png!
!screenshot-2.png!
!screenshot-3.png!

h4. Problem

Build is successful when Maven fails and tests are quarantined. It looks like using the 'Use Maven return code' feature is not working when used with quarantined tests. In the example below, Maven returned an error code but it looks like Bamboo ignored it, maybe mistaking it for a failed test.

h4. Steps to reproduce

Make sure that Maven tasks have 'Use Maven return code' checked. Run a build with quarantined tests. 

{noformat}
// this is correct
simple	23-Jan-2015 14:03:31	Failing task since return code of [/opt/maven-3.2/bin/mvn -Djava.io.tmpdir=/tmp/AMDN-AMDNRELEASE-JOB1 release:perform --batch-mode -DignoreSnapshots=true -Dresume=false] was 1 while expected 0
simple	23-Jan-2015 14:03:31	Parsing test results under /mnt/bamboo-ebs/bamboo-agent/build-dir/AMDN-AMDNRELEASE-JOB1...
simple	23-Jan-2015 14:03:31	Injected variable bamboo.mvn.release.releaseVersion=0.6.38 in RESULT scope
// this is not correct: all tests pass but maven had an error and did not produce any artifact
simple	23-Jan-2015 14:03:31	Changing Task Result to SUCCESS as all failed tests were quarantined.
{noformat}

Bamboo detects the task is failing (1st line of the exemple above), but doesn't mark the whole build as failed.

Currently you end up with an error in the new tab or window saying:

{quote}
Error encountered while triggering manual build: Could not generate next build number for '<plan key>'
Plan '<plan key>' did not start
{quote}

And no build is run.

A better solution could be to store the last exit code of a bamboo build task in a variable like
{code}
${bamboo.lastExitCode}
{code}
accessible in the final task.

To test it, run a script task with "exit 5" and a final script task with "echo %ERRORLEVEL%".

Suppose you set up a command and pass in the following arguments
{noformat}
-one:1 -args:two=2,three=3,username=myUser,password="quoted password",three=3
{noformat}
Bamboo will now escape these arguments by adding double quotes around them, and given the argument contains a quote already it causes the whole invocation to fail.
